======================================================================
PART 6: I(Omega, x) AS A TOURNAMENT CLASSIFIER
  Different tournaments have different Omega, hence different I(Omega, x)
  I(Omega, 2) = H(T), but I(Omega, x) for general x is MORE information
  Does I(Omega, x) (as a polynomial) determine the tournament class?
======================================================================

  n=5: I(Omega, x) = 1 + alpha_1 * x (alpha_2=0)
  So I(Omega, x) determined by H, and vice versa. No extra info.

  n=6: I(Omega, x) = 1 + alpha_1*x + alpha_2*x^2
  This is a QUADRATIC in x, giving 2 independent numbers (alpha_1, alpha_2).
  H = I(Omega, 2) = 1 + 2*alpha_1 + 4*alpha_2 conflates them into one number.
  The full polynomial I(Omega, x) is STRICTLY MORE INFORMATIVE than H at n>=6!

  n=5: 7 distinct I(Omega, x) polynomials
  n=5: 7 distinct H values
  Same count! (because alpha_2=0)

======================================================================
PART 7: THE 'NO ADJACENT 1s' CONSTRAINT
  In Zeckendorf: no two adjacent Fibonacci indices selected
  In OCF: no two conflicting cycles selected (independence)
  In the TILING model: what does 'no adjacent' mean?
======================================================================
  In the tiling model:
  - Two tiles (arcs) are 'adjacent' if they share a vertex
  - The 'no adjacent 1s' constraint would mean:
    no two backward arcs share a vertex
  - This is the INDEPENDENCE condition on the ARC conflict graph
    (different from the CYCLE conflict graph Omega!)

  The arc conflict graph has vertices = arcs, edges = shared vertex.
  This is the LINE GRAPH of the complete graph K_n.
  I(line(K_n), x) at x=1 counts independent sets of arcs = MATCHINGS of K_n!

  SO: The 'no adjacent 1s' constraint on arcs counts MATCHINGS.
  The 'no conflicting cycles' constraint on cycles counts INDEPENDENT CYCLE SETS.
  H = I(Omega, 2) bridges these two worlds!

  Matchings of K_n (= independent sets of line graph):
    K_2: 2 matchings (= I(line(K_2), 1))
    K_3: 4 matchings (= I(line(K_3), 1))
    K_4: 10 matchings (= I(line(K_4), 1))
    K_5: 26 matchings (= I(line(K_5), 1))
    K_6: 76 matchings (= I(line(K_6), 1))
    K_7: 232 matchings (= I(line(K_7), 1))

  Matching numbers: these are the TELEPHONE NUMBERS (involution counts)!

